Control flow statements determine the order in which statements are executed in a program.

C# supports several types:

1. Decision Making Statements

Used to make decisions based on conditions.

if

if-else

if-else if-else

switch

Example:

int age = 20;

if (age >= 18)
{
    Console.WriteLine("You are an adult");
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("You are not an adult");
}

2. Looping Statements

Used to repeat code.

for loop

while loop

do-while loop

foreach loop (for arrays, lists)

Example:

for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++)
{
    Console.WriteLine(i);
}

3. Jump Statements

Used to transfer control:

break â†’ exit loop

continue â†’ skip current iteration

goto â†’ jump to a label

Example:

for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++)
{
    if (i == 3) continue; // skip 3
    if (i == 5) break;    // stop loop
    Console.WriteLine(i);
}

4. Return Statement

Exits from a method and optionally returns a value.

int Sum(int x, int y)
{
    return x + y;
}

ðŸ›  Example Program
using System;

namespace ControlFlowDemo
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            int num = 7;

            // if-else
            if (num % 2 == 0)
                Console.WriteLine("Even");
            else
                Console.WriteLine("Odd");

            // switch
            switch (num)
            {
                case 1:
                    Console.WriteLine("One");
                    break;
                case 7:
                    Console.WriteLine("Seven");
                    break;
                default:
                    Console.WriteLine("Other number");
                    break;
            }

            // while loop
            int i = 1;
            while (i <= 3)
            {
                Console.WriteLine("While Loop: " + i);
                i++;
            }

            // for loop with continue
            for (int j = 1; j <= 5; j++)
            {
                if (j == 3) continue;
                Console.WriteLine("For Loop: " + j);
            }
        }
    }
}
